gomodel:SYNGO_2850  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.3: \"Epac2 interacts with GluR2/3-containing AMPAR and removes them from spines\"\n- \"Following 8-CPT treatment, GluR2/3 content became significantly reduced in spines (Fig. 3b), and increased in shaft clusters. These effects were specifically dependent on Epac2; RNAi-mediated knockdown prevented 8-CPT-induced GluR2/3 removal from spines (Fig. 3c) (*P<0.01). RNAi expression did not alter GluR2/3 spine content, suggesting that Epac2 activation is only involved in GluR2/3 removal from synapses\"\n\nFig.4: \"Epac2 activation depresses AMPAR-mediated synaptic transmission\"\n- \"To determine the functional outcome of this reduction in GluR2/3 content in spines, we examined the effects of 8-CPT on AMPAR-dependent miniature excitatory postsynaptic currents (mEPSCs) (Fig. 4). Incubation of neurons with 8-CPT (50 uM, 1 hr) resulted in a robust reduction of mean amplitudes (34%) and frequencies (59%) of AMPAR-mediated mEPSCs (Fig. 4a) (*P<0.05), resulting in a shift in the distribution of mEPSC amplitudes toward smaller values. RNAi-knockdown of Epac2 in postsynaptic neurons prevented 8-CPT-mediated reduction in basal mean mEPSC amplitude (Fig. 4a)\". Experimental description: - \"Dissociated cultures of primary cortical neurons were prepared from E18 Sprague-Dawley rat embryos and cultured as described1.\"\n- \"Coimmunoprecipitation from cortical pyramidal neurons were carried out essentially as described above...\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0593-3443" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2018-03-09" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_2850" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

